metadata.name: Shape Study  #86
metadata.description:
“Everyone has their own shape.”
We meet shapes of all kinds in our life.

Algorithmic randomness generates shapes ever so slightly different yet similar. 
I suppose these are someone’s collection.

“Why do they need to have so many similar things?”

Perhaps it’s their versatility in the pleasure they could bring.
Perhaps they’re meant for different occasions.
Perhaps some are left to search for their very own shapes.

Seeing this, I realized that when people explore themselves or others, it is also a form of shape study.
With what’s visible and concrete, explore the unseen and abstract.

However, good shapes only come by chance.
Shapes, in truth, cannot be good or bad in and of themselves. It’s only when two shapes come together that the meaning thereof arises.
I hope you who decide to pick up this work will find the shapes to your liking.

『每個人都有自己的形狀』
並且每個人一生中也會認識各種形狀

程式的隨機性讓我產生的每個形狀都相似而不同
我想像這也許是某個人的蒐藏
『為什麼會需要擁有這麼多相似的道具呢？』

也許是它們有著不同的功能，能帶來不同的愉悅；
也許是適用於不同的場景
也許是遲遲未找到屬於自己的形狀

想像至此，我意識到：當人們探索自己／他人的同時，也可以說是一種形狀研究
用一個看得見的具體，去探索一個看不見的抽象

然而，好的形狀是可遇不可求的
其實形狀本身沒有好壞，只有當兩個形狀相遇時，形狀才有了意義
希望蒐藏這件作品的各位都可以遇到喜歡的形狀

metadata.name: tratti #54
metadata.description:
"tratti" is an Italian word that has many different meanings. When we started working on this piece, we wanted to create something that combines our traits ("tratti" in Italian).
We had this urge to channel the turbulent times we're living in now into this artwork using just lines ("tratti" in Italian).

We don't know what to do now, we're here, and that's all that matters. We're here for our families, our friends, and our community. Like everything in life, there are joyful times and challenging times. We must accept happiness as something that is not constant but that we feel at times (a "tratti" in Italian).

With "tratti", we want to send a message to every disheartened human being: "Stay strong and never let anyone or anything crush the hope in you. Joyful times are around the corner".

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #80
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of François Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl

metadata.name: Echoes #48
metadata.description:
"The stars were also temporal travelers. How many of these ancestral flashes of light were echoes of long-gone suns? And how many awaited their birth, whose brightness had not yet reached us? If all the suns were to fade away, except for ours, how long would it take for us to realize our solitude? I always knew that the firmament harbored mysteries, but only now do I understand that the earth is also shrouded in enigmas."

Project created in p5.js
Press "s" to save the image.

metadata.name: Rural Places #36
metadata.description:
Continuing my exploration of abstract minimalism, this artwork is fully developed using p5js (100% code). Rural Places is a meditation in the form of abstract minimalism. There are 6 types of buildings and structures such as windmills and water towers and multiple houses with different structures and styles in this artwork. There are various arrangements and color palettes based on different times of the day.

To see the artwork in full size, It's highly recommended to open it in live mode.

You can save the artwork by pressing 's' in live view after render was completed.

metadata.name: heikō #56
metadata.description:
平衡 (heikō): Equilibrium

As someone with ADHD, focusing has always been a challenge for me. It's difficult for me to concentrate, especially when it comes to learning new things like p5.js. Despite the difficulty, I pushed through and managed to grasp the concepts, which was a significant accomplishment for me. To commemorate this personal milestone, I chose to incorporate the theme of focus into my first generative art token.

Drawing inspiration from my childhood hobbies, I decided to represent the concept of focus by stacking stones on top of each other. As a child, I found joy in this activity, and it served as a metaphor for the determination and concentration required to overcome challenges.

In addition to my personal connection, I also drew inspiration from the Japanese culture of zen, concentration, and focus. The overall theme of my generative art token reflects these principles, paying homage to the mindset of finding inner peace and clarity through focus and concentration.

By combining my personal journey with the symbolism of stacked stones and the Japanese culture of zen, I hope to convey the importance of focus and celebrate the achievement of overcoming obstacles, especially for individuals like myself who face unique challenges in maintaining concentration.

Please press ‘2’ to ‘7’ to change the resolution (max 5600 × 7000 px).
Use the key ’S’ to save the output as a PNG file.

metadata.name: Flowingcles #108
metadata.description:
"Flowingcles" is a generative art piece that showcases a mesmerizing collection of  circles and abstract shapes. This unique collection invites art enthusiasts to embark on an inspiring visual journey.

Some pieces feature abstract shapes accompanied by a noise effect, reflecting restlessness and energy, while others present a more serene atmosphere with minimalized noise effects. These two approaches offer collectors the freedom to choose the one that resonates with them the most.

The "Flowingcles" collection consists of a total of 128 original pieces. Each artwork has been generated with a unique combination, ensuring individuality and distinctiveness. By incorporating these pieces into their collections, art enthusiasts can adorn their homes, offices, or galleries with a sense of unparalleled art experience and authenticity.

"Flowingcles" stands as a prominent example of modern art, showcasing dynamism, aesthetics, and originality. This collection pushes the boundaries of art and takes viewers on a captivating visual journey. Therefore, me invite art lovers to explore the "Flowingcles" collection and become a part of this visual spectacle:)

- S: Save a png file with the current resolution (2400*3400)

metadata.name: Quadrangle of My Being #123
metadata.description:
This project began as an exploration of how human beings across all sorts of cultures respond in remarkably similar ways in terms of associating sounds with shapes.  That’s a project I will have to come back to. Along the way, the outputs started to remind me of landforms seen from high above and topographical maps of imaginary terrain - the terrain of my own being.

Though the work is algorithmic through and through, I have used elements of my analog photographic work as a bits and pieces of some layers.  These photographic works are chemigrams, and are generative in their own right, arising from semi-controlled chemical reactions on dark room paper in the presence of resists and light. These chemigrams are the first topos of my being, and bringing them into this work emphasizes something I have long wanted to pursue - the rich interplay of my analog and digital practices in search of unexplored territory.

Explore some territory - you just might find the quadrangle of your being.

Collection Mechanics:
In the initial week after launch, holders of any of my past fx(hash) projects may mint free editions to the extent of their reserves on a first come, first served basis.  Beginning in the 2nd week, any unclaimed editions will be offered for public sale. 

Minting Instructions: 
1) Use the Randomized Params button to explore outputs.  
2) When a design emerges that you want to mint, lock the Seed Input param.  
3) Mint & enjoy. 

Parameter Descriptions: 
Seed Input: Each output is a unique result based on your wallet address and the seed value. If you record the seed for a given output as you explore, you can simply type in the recorded seed to retrieve it.

Project Details:
Created by Wanda Oliver (wandaoliver.tez) in July, 2023, this work is licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

The minter shares secondary royalties with the creator and a beneficiary.

Interactions:
Press [D] in live mode to download.
Press [S] in live mode to download a high resolution output suitable for framing.
Press [F] in live mode to toggle the frame on and off.

metadata.name: RAA #53
metadata.description:
Since I started working on this project in April 2023, I've been asking myself if abstraction is an endless escape, I can't put into words the forms that RAA has brought me, the falcon-headed man inhabits a place in my head, which materializes in a mosaic of shattered glass.

Code made in hydra.ojack.xyz a realtime video synthesizer, inspired by modular synthesizers, by olivia jack, part of the sales will be donated to Hydra Foundation.

Soundtrack that accompanies the livecode can be played by clicking anywhere on the image, realized in vcvrack, a synthesizer simulator, based on eurorack(pre-rendered). Highly recommended to use a dedicated sound system or headphones. You can save a png 1920x1080 of the perpetual animation by pressing 'S'

metadata.name: Ode to Bugs and Happy Accidents #115
metadata.description:
“If debugging is the process of removing software bugs, then programming must be the process of putting them in.”

― Edsger W. Dijkstra


This artwork is dedicated to happy accidents, mistakes, and bugs. Every key part of it is based on some sort of failure: wrong variable value, unstopped recursion, untimely function call. And sometimes it leads to pleasant results.

It was created to celebrate #fxhashturnsone event.

The earnings are partly donated to:
- Processing Foundation
- #TezosStandsWithUkraine

[a] - toggle animation
[1] - save PNG in low resolution
[2] - save PNG in medium resolution
[3] - save PNG in high resolution
[4] - save PNG in ultra-high resolution

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js

By Collapsar Beauty
